<h2>The Recorder in the Basement</h2>
<p>
   Marcus found the cassette recorder while cleaning out his late grandfather’s basement during a thunderstorm. It was old, covered in dust, and labeled only with the date “October 14, 1987.” Curious, he inserted fresh batteries and pressed play. At first there was only static, but then he heard his grandfather’s voice whispering nervously about “something living behind the walls.” The recording ended abruptly with loud banging and a scream so distorted it sounded inhuman.
<br>
<p>
    That night, Marcus kept hearing faint tapping noises from inside the basement walls. Every few minutes, the recorder would suddenly click on by itself even though the batteries had been removed. This time the tape contained new audio that Marcus swore hadn’t been there before. Between bursts of static, he heard his own voice pleading for help and repeating, “Don’t let it mimic me.” Before the tape stopped, a second voice quietly laughed in the background.
</p>
<br>
<p>
    Panicked, Marcus ran downstairs to destroy the recorder, but the basement door slammed shut behind him. The lights flickered violently while scratching sounds echoed from inside the walls all around him. Then he heard his grandfather’s voice calling from the darkness, begging Marcus to come closer. As he backed away, dozens of pale fingers slowly pushed through the cracks in the wooden walls. The next morning, police found the basement empty except for the recorder still playing one final message: “Now it knows your voice too.”
</p>